abstract: In the On Politics newsletter: Nearly every candidate can stake a claim as the most electable. It just depends on how you think the election will be won.

abstract: It was pushed by Madison Avenue and preached by self-help gurus. Then it entered politics.
snippet: It was pushed by Madison Avenue and preached by self-help gurus. Then it entered politics.
lead_paragraph: If the supposedly unlikable Hillary Clinton didn’t break the highest, hardest glass ceiling in 2016, she made enough cracks in it to encourage others to try again: Six women are competing for the Democratic nomination today. But guess what? We don’t seem to like them either.

abstract: The former vice president is defending his friendliness toward Republicans in Washington, saying Mr. Trump doesn’t represent them. But others say that view is naïve.
snippet: The former vice president is defending his friendliness toward Republicans in Washington, saying Mr. Trump doesn’t represent them. But others say that view is naïve.
lead_paragraph: DUBUQUE, Iowa — As Joseph R. Biden Jr. made his way across Iowa on his first trip as a 2020 presidential candidate, the former vice president repeatedly returned to one term — aberration — when he referred to the Trump presidency.

abstract: Six of the 23 presidential candidates have appeared in The Times’s weddings pages. Care to guess which ones?
snippet: Six of the 23 presidential candidates have appeared in The Times’s weddings pages. Care to guess which ones?

abstract: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
snippet: It’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the stories you might have missed.
lead_paragraph: From William Barr’s charged hearing to the latest Democratic White House contender, it’s been a busy week in American politics. Here are some of the biggest stories you might have missed (and some links if you’d like to read further).
headline_main: On Politics: The Biggest Stories of the Week

abstract: Ms. Klobuchar said she was making addiction, including alcoholism and the opioid crisis, an early focus of her campaign in part because of her experience with her father’s alcoholism.
snippet: Ms. Klobuchar said she was making addiction, including alcoholism and the opioid crisis, an early focus of her campaign in part because of her experience with her father’s alcoholism.
lead_paragraph: Senator Amy Klobuchar on Friday released a $100 billion plan to combat drug and alcohol addiction and improve mental health care, focusing one of the first detailed proposals of her presidential campaign on an issue deeply personal to her.
